|  This album  = ''Footloose''<br />(2011)
|  Next album  =
}}
The original soundtrack was released by [[Atlantic Records]] and [[Warner Music Nashville]] on September 27, 2011. It includes eight new songs and four remakes of songs from the original film's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/archives/footloose_soundtrack_features_cee-lo_smashing_pumpkins_more_due_september_2/|title=<U+2018>Footloose<U+2019> Soundtrack Features Cee Lo, Smashing Pumpkins & More; Due September 27th|last= Davis|first=Edward|work=[[indieWire]]|publisher=[[Snagfilms]]|date=August 9, 2011|accessdate=September 24, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/61x5QSDRE|archivedate=September 24, 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Kenny Loggins]]' "[[Footloose (song)|Footloose]]" was covered by [[Blake Shelton]] for the remake, which is an upbeat country version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/blake-sheltons-footloose-cover-hits-231775|title="The Voice" coach puts a country spin on Kenny Loggins<U+2019> original for the upcoming film remake|last=Schillaci|first=Sophie|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 6, 2011|accessdate=September 24, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/61x4rOnm2|archivedate=September 24, 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref> The film opens with several teens dancing to Loggins' original version of the song. Like the original film, the 2011 version also features "[[Metal Health (song)|Bang Your Head (Metal Health)]]" by the [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Quiet Riot]] and the original "[[Let's Hear It for the Boy (song)|Let's Hear It For The Boy]]".

